Papua New Guinea Campaign :

From July - November 1942

Part of Japan’s Operation Mo, aimed to take over New Guinea and isolate Australia and New Zealand . 

The Australian forces tried to stop the Japanese southern advance down the Kokoda trail to protect Australia from being in bombing range . 

Resulted in heavy losses for the Japanese Army

Starvation and diseases claimed the majority of Japanese soldier’s lives, due to the dense, rainforest environment of New Guinea, and being subject to Allied naval blockades . 

Around 130,000 Japanese soldier died, only 40,000 Allied forces died

Battle of the Bulge : Dec 1944 - Jan 1945

Known as the Ardennes Counteroffensive

Axis troops traveled through the Ardennes region in Belgium and Luxembourg to try surprise the Allies and split the Allied lines, and encircle and destroy the Allied troops in Belgium . 

If successful, will help obtain a peace treaty in the German’s favours

Very successful initially, due to Allied overconfidence, their stubbornness to carry out their own offensive plans, and poor aerial reconnaissance 

Initial attack Germany : 410,000 men, 1,400 tanks

Initial attack Allied : 230,000 men, 500 tanks

But the battle was too late, and the German resources and weapons were severely depleted, and their production rates couldn’t quickly replace them . 

Severely depleted, German units retreated to the Siegfried Line . 

Around 60,000 - 100,00 German casualties, 90,000 Allied casualties


D-Day : June 6 1944

Codenamed Operation Overlord, biggest seaborne invasion in history . 

Preparations involved securing air control and dominance, learned from the failures of the Dieppe Raid, 1942

Strategic bombing used in early 1944

Eg : Big Week or Operation Argument : Sequence of US and RAF force bombing raids from 20-25 Feb 1944 . Whole week, dropped 10,000 tons of bombs
Operation Fortitude : British operation to try and misinform Germany of an invasion in Norway (Fortitude North) and Pas de Calais (Fortitude South)

Calais closer to England, tricked German

Fake code messages and dummy field armies in South England . 

Pluto (Pipe line under the sea) - fuel pipeline under the sea

Mulberry Harbours, Hobart’s funnies - Specialised armour vehicles


Overnight, specialist troops parachuted in to capture vital bridges, road intersections and other positions eg gliders troops at pegasus bridge

Next were massive air attacks by over 12,000 planes and naval bombardments

Then 130,000 Allied soldiers transported across by sea, 23,000 by air, 12,000 casualties

Five invasion groups : Utah, Omaha (American), Gold, Sword (Britain), Juno (Canadian)

Germany only had 9,000 casualties, but poor supplies meant they had to retreat .


Importance of D-Day :

It was the largest seaborne invasion of history

The Holocaust :

The Holocaust, or the Shoah, was the genocide of European Jews in WW2 . 

From 1939-1945, around 6 million European Jews were killed by Nazi Germany and her collaborators. 

The Nazi studied social Darwinism, and claimed the white Aryans were the destined superior races, and claimed that Jews were inferior and needed to be cleansed out of Nazi society . 

Starting with Dachau in March 1933, Germany began building networks of camps for those deemed undesirable to society 

The passing of the Nuremberg Laws in 1935 .

Two laws :

The Law for the Protection of German Blood and German Honour : forbids marriage and sexual relations between Jews and Germans

The Reich Citizenship Law : Took away Jewish rights of citizenship, and strip the economically


Kristallnacht : the Night of the Broken Glass, 1938

The SA paramilitary force unleashed a spontaneous backlash at the Jewish citizens, using the shooting of a German embassy member as an excuse

Over 30,000 Jews arrested and sent to concentration camps

7,500 Jewish shops were smashed and destroyed

1,000 synagogues were destroyed

The Jewish community had to pay a huge fine for “causing” the destruction


Segregation of Jews in Ghettos : 

After the onset of WW2, Germany decided to deal with the new Jewish citizens by setting up ghettos to segregated them

They were put into the poorest parts of cities, and were walled off . 

Poor food, overcrowding, and hygiene

Around 5000 deaths each month in just the Warsaw ghetto, overall a total of 600,000 estimated deaths in the various ghettos .  


Einsatzgruppen : (special task forces)

Special task forces were sent out into Germany and her territories to round up and shoot any Jews found . 

4 units of 20,000 men, under SS authority . 

Much help from desperate locals, who wants the rewards of informing

Jew taken to a countryside location, forced to strip in huge pits, gunned down, and then covered back up with dirt . 

1 million Jews killed this way, but inefficient and had huge psychological impacts


Wannsee Conference : January 1942 

It became clear that the war with Russia would take longer than expected . The plan to ship Jews to Siberian labour camps wasn’t possible anymore . 

Purpose of Wannsee Conference to devise a new plan .

Decision to implement Die Endlosung ( The Final Solution )

Operation Reinhard in place from July 1942 : The movement of jews from ghetto to camps

The plan to systematically exterminate Jewish people in designed death camps . 

Jews transported in packed freight trains to extermination camps, where they were gassed, worked to death, died of starvation and disease, used for medical experiments or forced on death marches . 

Extermination camps located in the Bloodlands, the region of Eastern Europe from the Baltic states, to Poland, to the Black Sea . 

Jews convinced they were just sent to work - desperately believed . 

Extermination camps such as Auschwitz- Birkenau, and Belzec 


Why did the Holocaust happen ?

General evil hatred, racism, usage of Jews as a scapegoat, eugenics

Operations had been used to persecute Jews, Gypsies, Homosexuals, and others deemed inferior

Propaganda - Large amount of Nazi propaganda centred on the blaming of the Jews, the final solution carried on what they promised

Economic motive - They did not have to feed and support Jews . Mass extermination removed the cost of moving and planning logistics 

5-6 mil Jews died, 11-17 million people in total died by Holocaust .


Intentionalists : Argued there was a master plan by Hitler on how to deal with the Jewish . Argued the decision for the Jewish problem was given by authorities above, and the likes of Hitler . Hitler personally encouraged anti-semitism . 

Otherwise, he wouldn’t have continued on the final solutions, einsatzgruppen, etc

Functionalists : Argued there wasn’t a master plan by Hitler on how to deal with the Jewish . Argued the decision for the Jewish problem was developed all around by the lower ranks of German bureaucracy . It wasn’t solely Hitler’s vision . 

Hitler never signed anything explicitly . Planned came up by Reinhard and Himmler

KQ:10 (SKIPPING KQ9: HOW FAR WAS STALIN’S TO BLAME FOR STARTING AND SPREADING THE COLD WAR)

 

 

How successful was the USA’s policy of

containment in Korea?

The events and significance of the

﻿Korean War

After the collapse of Japan in 1945 after World War Two, the USSR invaded Korea and dismantled all ﻿Japanese control rapidly, starting from the north. Frightened of losing the entire country to communism, Truman asked them to stop once they reached the 38th parallel, which Stalin agreed to. This left Korea divided. The communist party was established in North Korea, under the power of Kim Il Sung. Truman quickly got to work in Europe with the Truman Doctrine, protecting countries against the flow of communism. Although it wasn’t active in Asia, it showed the USSR that America would stop at nothing to contain communism at all financial costs. In 1947 the UN gave Korea independence and organised a commission to oversee elections there. However Stalin refused to allow them into North Korea so the elections were only held to great a National Government for Korea in the south. In 1948, the US withdrew from Korea and the USSR also began to withdraw within that year. The elections took place in the middle of wide corruption and violent outbreaks in Korea. Syngman Rhee gained a majority vote in the National Assembly and became the new president. The UN recognised this new Republic of Korea. However in the North, the Soviets formed the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea. Kim Il Sung was the leader and known as the Premier. The UN refused to acknowledge this. In 1949, China became communist which was a huge victory for the USSR. The US became increasingly worried about their domino theory and about how the rest of Asia would surely fall to communism. However, the USSR would not give Kim Il Sung the support to invade South Korea, despite the increasing violence along the north/south border: 400 soldiers had been killed in May 1949 alone. In 1950, the US began to feel they needed to adopt a more aggressive policy than containment. They wanted to focus on rolling communism back and to reclaim areas that had fallen to the communists for democracy. However, they made the mistake of excluding Korea from their conversations in the field of strategic defence which led the Russians to believe they would not take action there.

On the 25th of June 1950, North Korea invaded South Korea. Propaganda from the north insisted that they only retaliated to an attack from the south but there was no proof of this. Truman was outraged and saw it as a bluff to test how the US would react and did not want to make the mistakes of appeasement in the 1930s. He got permission from the UN to intervene and this was granted on account of the USSR not being present to say otherwise because they were protesting the refusal to admit China to the UN. The North army pushed into the south quickly and efficiently and captured the capital, Seoul, in three days. By early September, the South Koreans had been forced into the very corner of the country at Pusan and were losing before the Americans even intervened. The Inchon Landings were led by General MacArthur who decided the best option would be to sever communications in the Northern army and cut them in two.He forced them to retreat from Pusan. This led to the reestablishment of a democratic government in South Korea and in the recapture of Seoul. The North army retreated and by the 1st of October 1950 the US and UN troops were back to the 38th parallel. The US was left with two options: containment or rollback. They chose rollback after getting the go ahead from the UN and invaded North Korea. Truman tried to ease the risk of the war by insisting the US would not invade China or the USSR. However China still protested and dispatched troops to the North Korean border in protest of having US troops too close to them. MacArthur insisted that China would not act. However on the 14th of October, 300,000-500,000 Communist Party Volunteers crossed over the Yalu River and began to attack the UN and US forces who were taken entirely by surprise. A state of emergency was declared in America. Truman was unwilling to engage in war with China but could not abandon Korea. He also did not want to resort to using the Atomic Bomb on Korea. That may have brought the USSR into the conflict which likely would have started World War Three. MacArthur would not stand for this reluctance however and took matters into his own hands, sending a letter to Beijing threatening China with nuclear war. Truman fired MacArthur immediately. After the war became a stalemate, a peace talk was opened up in Kaesong in July. Violence continued while these talks took place and the talks eventually broke down. They were resumed a year later in Panmunjom butagain were delayed specifically over where the demarcation line would be drawn and what would happen to prisoners of war.The US became committed to gaining control of the skies and they had managed to gain most of the control by 1952. They began to bomb hydroelectric plants and military targets in the northern capital Pyongyang. 

Despite their efforts to keep it localised on military targets, Kim Il Sung announced that 6000 civilians had been killed publically which sparked international outcry and made the Americans look bad. Truman’s reputation was ruined and he decided not to run for president again, stepping back to allow Republican Eisenhower to take over. Meanwhile, Stalin died in 1953 which signalled new hope for the western powers. On the 16th of June 1953, there were agreements for an armistice. This was not the end of the conflict however. Syngman Rhee opposed many of the compromises made but he was eventually silenced by the promise of a 1 billion dollar investment into stopping the spread of communism in Asia. On the 27th of July, the armistice was signed by China, America and North Korea. South Korea would not sign it but had to accept it anyway.

 

The Cuban Missile Crisis (containment of Communism)

 

Cuba, small island 90 Km from the coast of Florida

US ally, US businesses, US military Base (Guantanamo)

In 1959, Fidel Castro overthrew US backed dictator Battista and established a Cuban Communist Government.

 

Then, Castro took over US businesses 

250,000 wealthy Cubans left Cuba

Castro did not keep his promise of holding free and fair elections in Cuba claiming that National Unity had been achieved

In March 1960, pres. Eisenhower approved a CIA plan to overthrow Castro, over 400 officers were employed full time under this plan and there were over 20 attempts to kill Castro which all failed. 

*JANUARY 1961: US broke off diplomatic relations with Cuba.

*APRIL 14, 1961: US planes bombed Cuba’s airfields after the US bombing Cuba was only left with 8 planes and 7 pilots.

*Just 2 days later, on April 16 1961, 5 ships carrying 1400 CIA trained cuban exiles were brought to the Bay of pigs they were faced by 20,000 Cuban soldiers with modern weapons and Soviet tanks.

  • The attack was a total failure as 2 Ships were sunk, including one of them carrying important supplies.

  • 2 aircrafts shot down which were providing air cover to the ground forces of the exiles

  • Everyone had been surrendered, wounded or killed within 72 hours

What was the consequence of the attack?

  • Khruschev  ridiculed US’ Pathetic Attempt of getting rid of communism in Cuba

  • It made the current US pres. Kennedy look ineffective 

  • It made castro and communism more popular in Cuba

  • Krushchev and Castro grew more suspicious of the USA

  • Khruschev and Castro became more closer allies

 

About one year later on May 1962, USSR announced publicly that it was sending weapons to Cuba and by Sep 1962, Cuba was the best equipped nation in South America.(Thousands of non-nuclear missiles, Tanks, boats, radar stations, 5000 soviet technicians to train Cubans)

 

USA, yes, could do nothing and on 11 september warned USSR that he would prevent installation of nuclear missiles on cuba by whatever means possible and USSR replies saying they have no intention of placing missiles on Cuba (US greatly believed that the USSR would not dare to install Nuclear Missiles but this was not the case)

 

October 1962: THE OCTOBER CRISIS

  • 14 october 1952, A US- U2 spy plane took photos of missile sites over Cuba, to intelligence experts it was very clear that these were meant for nuclear missiles, being built by the USSR and could be ready in 7 days although some were already ready to fire.

Outcome

-Cuba remained Communist and heavily armed without N missiles

- Cuba had gone from relying on the USA to relying on USSR

-although Kruschev had made Kennedy remove missiles from Greece and Turkey, it still made him look ineffective in public leading to his dismissal in 1964
